    "instruction": "Using pandas, compute global thresholds per component-KPI from metric.csv as follows: (1) group by cmdb_id and kpi_name across the full metric.csv and calculate P95 and P5 for each group (use the entire available series for threshold calculation). (2) Parse the incident window start and end as UTC datetimes: start = '2024-01-20 13:34:02' UTC, end = '2024-01-20 14:04:02' UTC; then filter metric.csv rows whose timestamps are within [start, end] (parse timestamps with pd.to_datetime(..., unit='s', utc=True)). (3) For each component-KPI group, count anomalous points within the incident window where value >= P95 (high anomalies) and where value <= P5 (low anomalies). Also compute for each group: earliest_high_timestamp (first timestamp in window where value>=P95), earliest_low_timestamp (first timestamp where value<=P5), max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window, and the global P95 and P5. (4) Return a compact table of groups that have anomaly counts > 0, with columns: cmdb_id, kpi_name, p95, p5, anomaly_high_count, anomaly_low_count, earliest_high_timestamp, earliest_low_timestamp, max_value_in_window, min_value_in_window. Limit output to top 20 rows sorted by (anomaly_high_count + anomaly_low_count) descending. Also return the total number of distinct component-KPI groups processed and confirm trace.csv and error_logs.csv are empty."
}

{
    "analysis": "From the previous Executor output, many infrastructure/messaging components (rabbitmq, rabbitmq-exporter, queue-master) and some DBs (catalogue-db, session-db) show strong anomalies across the incident window. However, per the diagnosis rules the root-cause component must be one of the service-level candidates (carts, catalogue, orders, payment, user). The metric summary already shows service-level anomalies for: catalogue (socket), orders (error), payment (diskio and socket), user (socket), and front-end (error) — front-end is not in the allowed root-cause list but its error KPI may indicate user-facing impact. We must now narrow to only the allowed candidate services and quantify their metric anomalies within the incident window (P95/P5 computed on full series, then count anomalies inside the window) to identify which service(s) are truly faulty and when their faults start.",
